{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-20147/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-20147"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["2:01:47"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["close-up"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman smiles at a man offscreen."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-20147","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-20147"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1/b53e569f-c459-4be9-999d-bcda0a88c4bd","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:52:28.636Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Writing about <em>Phantom Thread</em> and Karen Russell’s short story “Reeling for the Empire,” Amy Greenhough observes, “What these two contemporary narratives suggest, however, is that a woman’s creativity is stifled by the working systems of capitalism, and that the way to challenge ‘commodified abstract labour’ as ‘disembodied, detached from the persons who perform it’ (14), is to recognize labor as an embodied act, not alienated from the self but fully a part of it. It is only when Kitsune and Alma bring their identities, feelings, desires, and the darkness and resistance that come with these, to their work (and in Alma’s case, her relationship) that they can reclaim both their bodies and their lives from their masters. Alma can relish giving ‘every piece’ (Anderson 0.01.26) of herself when she knows she can ask for (and take) the same” (Greenhough, “Spinning Bodies into Gold,” 202). Alma, in other words, finds peace, joy, and power as she takes hold of Reynolds’s body through her poisoning and, then, through the care she provides him.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20147/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:551.4339114832535,19.99028110047834,660.9374999999999,911.5662380382776"}}}]}]}]}